def as_image(x):
    """Convert an ndarray to an Image.
    
    Args:
        x (ndarray): The array of pixels.
        
    Returns:
        Image: The Image object.
    """
    return Image.fromarray(np.uint8(x))

Exercise 1.1. How many dimensions does the cat array have? What does each dimension represent?

In [8]:
# get dimensions of cat array
cat.shape
Out[8]:
(267L, 400L, 3L)

267L is the height (267 rows of pixles) and 400L is the width of the image (400 columns of pixles). The 3L represents the 3 color variables there are (R, G, B).

Exercise 1.2. Use .copy() to copy the cat array to a new variable. Swap the green and blue color channels in the copy. Display the result.

In [9]:
# make a copy of the cat array
cat_copy = cat.copy()

# for each row of the color dimension, swap the second and third columns
for row in range(cat_copy.shape[0]):
    for column in range(cat_copy.shape[1]):
        # we want to only swap the colors, which is why we swap the 3rd dimension of the cat array
        cat_copy[row, column, 1], cat_copy[row, column, 2] = cat_copy[row, column, 2], cat_copy[row, column, 1]

print cat_copy

# display the resulting image
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
plt.imshow(cat_copy)

Exercise 1.3. Why is .copy() necessary in exercise 1.2? What happens if you don't use .copy()?

It is necessary in Exercise 1.2. to use .copy() because doing cat_copy = cat may result in changing the oringal cat variable. So .copy() creates a different copy. It guarentees to not be the same as the variable cat.

Exercise 1.4. Flip the blue color channel from left to right. Display the resulting image. Hint: see the NumPy documentation on array manipulation routines.

The cell blow flips the blue color channel from left to right. The for loop selects the rows of cat_copy, so now we have row, which is only two dimensions instead of three like cat_copy. Numpy fliplr only flips 2-D and on (it ignores the 1-D) so it will only flip 2-D in row, which is the colors. Numpy fliplr will cause R-G-B to become B-G-R.

In [10]:
import numpy as np

for row in range(cat_copy.shape[0]):
    cat_copy[row] =  np.fliplr(cat_copy[row])

# display the resulting image
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
plt.imshow(cat_copy)
plt.show()

Part 2: Singular Value Decomposition¶

Exercise 2.1. Write the functions described below.

  • A function that takes a matrix $X$ and returns its principal component matrix $XV_q$ and basis matrix $V_q^T$. This function should also take the number of terms kept $q$ as an argument.

  • A function that takes a principal component matrix $XV_q$ and basis matrix $V_q^T$ and returns an approximation $\hat{X}$ for the original matrix.

For Exercise 2.1. only, I worked with Sierra Tevlin, Chad Pickering, Hannah Kosinovsky, Nivi Achanta, and Richard Safran.

In [13]:
# make another copy of the cat image
cat_copy_2 = cat.copy()

x = np.array(cat_copy_2)
# get only the red channel
x = x[:,:,0]

# function that gets the principital component and basis matrix
def get_princ_basis_matrix(x,q):
    # get vt from svd()
    u, d, vt = np.linalg.svd(x)
    # get V_q
    basis_matrix = vt[:q]
    # get X * V_q
    prince_matrix = x.dot(np.transpose(basis_matrix))
    return [prince_matrix, basis_matrix]

# set both the principal component and basis matrix to have only p terms to create an estimate cat image
prince_matrix, basis_matrix = get_princ_basis_matrix(x, 10)

# get the approximation of X^hat for the original matrix
def estX(prince_matrix, basis_matrix):
    # multiplies (X * V_q) * V^T_q to get approximation of X^hat
    x_hat = prince_matrix.dot(basis_matrix)
    return x_hat

# plugs in the principal componment and basis matrix to get an estimate of X
x_hat = estX(prince_matrix, basis_matrix)
as_image(x_hat)
Out[13]:

As $q$ increases (more terms/columns from $V_q$ are kept), the image becomes less blurry. The image looks best when $q$ is around 350 and above.

Exercise 2.2. You can check the number of bytes used by a NumPy array with the .nbytes attribute. How many bytes does the red color channel of the cat image use? How many bytes does the compressed version use when 10 terms are kept? What percentage of the original size is this?

In [48]:
print cat_copy[:,:,2].nbytes # bytes of the red color channel of the cat image
print cat_copy.nbytes # bytes of the original cat image
print prince_matrix.nbytes + basis_matrix.nbytes # the compressed version when 10 terms are kept of the cat image

106800
320400
53360

The red color channel of the cat image uses 106800 bytes, which is exactly $\frac{1}{3}$ of the original size. The original is 320400 bytes. The compressed version when 10 terms are kept has 53360 bytes. This is $\frac{53360}{320400} = 0.16654 = 16.65\%$ of the original image.
